MissionCommands.Message: Welcome to the Atmospheric Entry lesson! This is an involved lesson that covers many systems working together to bring the Command Module through the atmosphere.
You are currently in a ~220 nmi x ~220 nmi circular orbit around the Earth.

During entry, the attitude of the craft is important. We need to ensure that our heat shield is facing the direction of flight, while also having a good control of roll. Roll is what we will use to control how the craft flies through the atmosphere.

Two forms of entry exist, Earth Entry and Lunar Entry. Today we will learn how to perform an Earth Entry as we are in orbit around Earth. Lunar Entry is performed if you are comming back from the Moon.
I will guide you through the entire procedure using the actual checklists, so you will not use the RUN feature at all today.

Let us get started. The first checklist is the Mission Pad -> Checklists -> (AoH) Command Module -> EARTH ENTRY: EARTH ORBIT ENTRY VEHICLE, feel free to keep it open as a reference, but do not use the RUN feature.
The main events of an Earth Entry is to plan the deorbit burn, prepare the craft for entry, separate from the Service Module, atomspheric entry, and landing.
All Earth entries should have an entry interface angle of about 2 degrees. We will soon plan this.
As the entry procedures are quite busy, and time is limited, I recommend you to use the TIMESCALE 0.5x (CTRL+SHIFT+F1 by default) if desired.
Open the CSM Burn Planner and plan an entry burn with an entry interface angle of about 2 degrees. Set the phase to 260, the dV to 454, the direction to RETROGRADE.
Take a note of the "Time of CM/SM sep" time stamp, then press REQUEST. You will receive two messages containing the burn parameters, press ROGER on both.
Open CREW MEMBERS -> REQUEST PADS & CHARTS -> OPEN P30 MANEUVER PAD FORM, close the CREW MEMBERS menu and on the P30 MANEUVER PAD window, press Autoplot to store the PAD in the form.
We will use the Digital Event Timer to aid us through the entry preparations.
STOP the Event Timer.
Then RESET the Event Timer to set it back to 00:00.
Set the Event Timer to count DOWN (when started later).
Flipping the EVENT TIMER MIN switch to TENS will increase it by 10 minutes.
Flipping the EVENT TIMER MIN switch to UNITS will increase it by 1 minute.
Flipping the EVENT TIMER SEC switch to TENS will increase it by 10 seconds.
Flipping the EVENT TIMER SEC switch to UNITS will increase it by 1 second.
Use these switches to set the Event Timer to 59:59. If you make a mistake, flip the RESET switch and try again. Press ROGER when the Event Timer is set to 59:59.

The SM/CM separation should happen 15 minutes before Entry Interface (EI). Take the "Time of CM/SM sep" from the Burn Planner and subtract 1 hour from it, and take a note of the result. If "Time of CM/SM sep" was 002:50:12, then the Event Timer should start at 001:50:12. We will get back to this soon but take a note of this time stamp as well.
The Entry Monitoring System (EMS) is an important tool used to track our entry profile, and it needs to run through a few steps. I recommend having a stop watch available for this procedure.
We will now test its functionality. Set the EMS Function switch to EMS TEST 1.
Wait 5 seconds while the EMS Function switch is in EMS TEST 1.
Set the EMS Mode switch to NORMAL.
Wait 10 seconds.
Set the EMS Function switch to EMS TEST 2.
Wait 10 seconds.
The .05G light should now illuminate.
Set the EMS Function switch to EMS TEST 3.
Wait 10 seconds.
The .05G light should still illuminate, and the lower Roll Stability Indicator (RSI) light located below the large arrow pointing up on the EMS should also illuminate.
Next we will set the ΔV/RANGE value on the EMS to prepare for the next test. Use the thumb rocker to adjust the value, try to press the upper part of it now.
The thumb rocker has 4 internal switches to Increase and Decrease the value by 10 or 0.1.
Use it to set the ΔV/RANGE value to 58.0. Press ROGER when complete.
Set the EMS Function switch to EMS TEST 4.

Wait 10 seconds. A scribe containing Test Patterns and entry profile graphs (not yet visible) will move and a device will draw a line on it along with the test pattern. The Range indicator will go down towards ~0.0.
The .05G light will still be illuminated, all others should be off.
Set the EMS Function switch to EMS TEST 5.
Wait 10 seconds.
The .05G light should be on, and the upper RSI (Roll Stability Indicator) light should be on.
Next we will adjust the scroll so that the line aligns with the Entry Profile pattern. In this EMS Function, pressing the thumb rocker will move the scroll.

Move the scroll left by pressing the two upper parts of the thumb rocker. Eventually you will see a scale on its lower section, starting from ~38. This is the velocity scaled by 1000, so 38 can be read as 38.000 ft/s. Align the line on the EMS scroll display with the line on the 37 mark (37.000 ft/s).
This marks the beginning of the entry profile. We will later tune this.
Set the EMS Function switch to RNG SET.
Then flip the EMS Mode switch back to standby (STBY). This completes the EMS checks before entry. It is now ready to be configured, something we will do after the deorbit burn.
Next we will activate the primary and secondary water evaporator.
Check that the GLY DISCH SEC PRESS is 39-51 psig.
Check that the SEC GLY EVAP OUT TEMP is 38-50.5°F.
Switch back to the primary ECS indicators.

As mentioned earlier the Digital Event Timer should be started exactly one hour before the CM/SM time stamp. Monitor the Mission Time (GET) and press ROGER 5 seconds before it reaches the CM/SM -1 hour time stamp calculated earlier (feel free to use time scale). If the time has passed, press ROGER now.
Start the Event Timer.
Next we will preheat the CM RCS jets. This is usually done about 1 hour before CM/SM sep.
The heaters are now on. You should leave them ON for 20 minutes. Move up to the Event Timer, then use timescale until the Event Timer reads ~40:00 minutes.
Next we will check the pyro batteries.
Ensure PYRO BAT A is > 34 vdc.
Ensure PYRO BAT B is > 34 vdc.
Then we will connect BATTERY C to Main Bus A and Main Bus B.
Next we will go through some circuit breaker configurations required before entry.
Then we will activate the CM RCS. This is the system that will be responsible for attitude control after CM/SM separation.
Check that the CM RCS 1 He PRESS is stable at 3300-3500 psia.
Check that the CM RCS 2 He PRESS is stable at 3300-3500 psia.
Next we will jettison the docking ring.
Use the attitude control stick to manually maneuver to Roll 0, Pitch 180, Yaw 0. Press ROGER when in attitude.
Then Yaw +45° out of plane (it does not matter if you yaw left or right). Press ROGER when in attitude.
Next we will jettison the docking ring (visual model not yet implemented but this step needs to be completed still).

This completes the first preparation checklist. Next we will prepare and execute the Deorbit Burn. The checklist is the EARTH ENTRY: SPS DEORBIT & ENTRY, feel free to reference this as we go through the steps, but do not use the RUN feature.
On the DKSY, key V37E 30E to start P30.
P30 should start by displaying V06 N33. The three registers will show the time to ignition in hours, minutes and seconds.
Press PRO.
P30 will display V06N81, the Impulsive Delta V at TIG in Local Vertical Coordinates.
This is used to set the amount of delta V burn in a vector format, allowing the burn to happen in a given direction. We wish to burn in the retrograde direction.
The value is already populated by Mission Control after using the burn tool. You can ignore the minor differences.
Press PRO to accept the values. The computer will spend a few seconds on calculations before displaying V06N42.
V06N42 shows the Ap and Pe altitude, and the magnitude of the dV burn. Our Pe should be negative as we target a burn to bring our craft through the atmosphere. Press PRO to continue.
V16N45 is now displayed, and shows the time to ignition in R2.
Press PRO to accept, the CMC will now automatically start P00.
Next we will go through some pre-separation checks.
We will ensure the OXYGEN REPRESS tank is filled with oxygen before we stage from the SM.
Monitor the OXYGEN REPRESS PRESSURE gauge on panel 602 (above and behind the headrest of the center seat). Let it fill to the green zone.
Then connect it to the O2 loop by setting it to ON.
This will cut off the SM O2 SUPPLY.
Next is the CM RCS CHECK. This is used to verify that the CM RCS functions before separating from the Service Module (CM/SM Sep).
Transfer the attitude control to the CM RCS.

Use the attitude control stick to test that you can maneuver in ROLL left and right, PITCH up and down, YAW left and right. Monitor the rate indicators on FDAI 1 to verify this, and press ROGER when complete.
Transfer the attitude control back to the SM RCS.
Next we will prepare for the SPS thrusting.
First step is to cycle the cryo fans.
Leave it on for 1 minute.
Leave it on for 1 minute.
Leave it on for 1 minute.
Leave it on for 1 minute.
Then set up the DAP. Key V48E V21E 11102E V22E 11111E PRO V32E
Key V37E 52E to start program 52. We will align the IMU with the preferred attitude (burn direction).
Wait for V04 N06 to display.
Key V22E 1E PRO PRO
Then we will maneuver to the burn direction, attitude 0,0,0. Key V49E and verify attitude is set to all zeros. Then press PRO to see V50.
Set the CMC mode to AUTO.
Press PRO to start the auto maneuver.
V06 will display indicating that the maneuver has started. Wait for it to complete. When V50 is displaying, press ENTR to complete the routine.
Next we will start P40 to prepare executing the burn. Key V37E 40E to start P40.
V50 N18 will display requesting the automaneuver (it is normal to do this again after V49).
Press PRO to accept. V50 will change to V06, and back to V50 when complete.
Press PRO again for a final trim. V50 will change to V06, and back to V50 when complete.
Press GDC align to align the GDC with the IMU. The simplified GDC align is configured (ATT SET to IMU) in this lesson.
Verify that the GDC is aligned with the IMU.
We are now ready to proceed with the burn preparations, quite similar to any other SPS burns.
Set the EMS to ΔV SET.
Use the thumb rocker to set the ΔV to the deorbit burn dV (from the P30 PAD, 454 ft/s).
Set the EMS to ΔV.
On the P30 PAD, check the Time of Ignition (TIG), it should be ~002:39:16 (this might differ slightly for you), and time scale to 6 minutes before the burn.
Then we will need change to our power source. So far in this mission, the Fuel Cells has been the primary source of power.
Since these are located in the Service Module, we will lose them when we separate it. The Entry and Post Landing batteries will take over as the primary power source.
These are located inside the Command Module. To tie them to the Main Bus, set the Main Bus Tie A/C switch to UP.
You might recall that it is common to tie these before any other SPS burn. The difference now is that we will leave them tied after the SPS Deorbit Burn is complete.
The batteries should now be powering the Command Module along with the Fuel Cells. However, the Fuel Cells will be jettisoned with the Service Module after CM/SM separation.
N18 should still be displaying on the DSKY. Press ENTR to proceed to the gimbal check.
V50 N25 should display 00204 in register 1. Press PRO to proceed with the gimbal test.
The gimabl test will move the gimbals through a test pattern. This takes a few seconds and the DSKY will display N40 when complete, showing the time to ignition.
Wait until you are 2 minutes away from ignition.
35 seconds before ignition, the DSKY will blank for 5 seconds. Press ROGER when the display returns at 30 seconds before ignition.
5 seconds before ignition V99 will show. At this moment, press PRO to allow the ignition.
Deorbit burn ignition!
Monitor the burn and wait for cutoff (C/O).
Cutoff, deorbit burn complete! We will now proceed with the post-burn checks.
Press PRO on the DSKY until P00 is automatically started to complete P40.

On the DSKY, key V82E to view Ha (R1) and Hp (R2) (Apogee and Perigee). Verify that Ha is about 220 nmi alt, and Hp is 0 nmi alt. If this is not the case, the burn was not correct and you will need to restart the lesson.
Key V37E 00E to return to P00.

As the Deorbit Burn is complete, we can get the Entry PAD. This will contains all of the important parameters and information needed during entry. Press CREW MEMBERS -> REQUEST PADS & CHARTS -> REQUEST ENTRY PAD. Press ROGER on the PAD message.
Then press CREW MEMBERS -> REQUEST PADS & CHARTS -> OPEN ENTRY PAD FORM and click Autoplot to fill the pad with the parameters just received.

The IMU needs a specific orientation during Entry. We will use P52 option 2 to align it to the Local Vertical as we pass the point of Entry Interface (400k ft altitude). The Entry Interface marks the start of our atmospheric entry where the density of the atmosphere will start to generate drag.
If you look at the PAD, a parameter containing a time stamp named RRT is the time of Entry Interface (EI) passing. We will use this to align the IMU.
Key V37E 52E to start P52.
Wait for V04 N06.
Key V22E 2E PRO to select and proceed with option 2.
V06 N34 will display. This is the time stamp to where we want to align the IMU with the Local Vertical.
We will now input the three RRT values (hours, minutes, seconds) using V25E. Key V25E.

Do not input anything yet. Looking at the RRT, the hours part will need to go into R1, the minutes into R2 and the seconds into R3. Your values might differ but if RRT is set to 003:05:04, R1 needs to be set to +3, R2 to +5 and R3 to +400. R3 is formatted as 000.00 so 4 seconds is 4.00, so 400.
Set the values according to the RRT parameter. Key +3E +5E +400E but change the data to match your own PAD.
Verify the data and then press PRO.
V06 N22 will now display the torquing values. Press PRO to accept and return to P00.

Then press GDC Align to align the GDC with the IMU. It is important that the GDC is aligned with the IMU or else the Rate Stability Indicator (RSI) arrow will be wrong, and entry guidance will not work correctly.
Next we will automaneuver to the entry attitude. Key V49E to start the routine, then V22E to change pitch to 209.00 degrees by inserting +20900E.

Verify the values and press PRO PRO to start the automaneuver. V50 will change to V06 to indicate the maneuver has started, then return to V50 when complete. Press ROGER when the maneuver is complete (V50 is shown after V06).
Then press ENTR to complete the routine and return to P00.
We will now prepare for CM/SM separation and maneuver to CM/SM separation attitude. This is +45 yaw from the entry attitude you are currently in.
Yaw +45° from the current attitude (it does not matter if you yaw left or right). Press ROGER when done.
We will now configure some last systems before separation.
The initial program to prepare for entry is P61, the Entry Preparation program. Key V37E 61E to start it.

The first input will be the predicted latitude and longitude of the splashdown location, and the last is if the initial entry will be heads up (+1) or heads down (-1). This controls the initial lift vector.
The capsule has been designed to have an aerodynamic lift vector, and is opposite of the direction of the heads. So if the heads are pointing down, the vector points up.
This vector is used to maneuver the capsule during entry, just like an aeroplane.
Press PRO to accept the default values.
Next, V06N60 shows predictions for entry, like the predicted g-force, velocity at entry interface and flight path angle between the inertial velocity and the local horizontal at the entry interface.
Press PRO to accept the values. The next screen shows more predictions like range to go from 0.05g, the predicted velocity at 0.05g and time until 0.05g.
Press PRO to accept. P61 now automatically moves to P62 - the CM/SM Separation and Preentry Maneuver.
P62 first displays V50N25, with 41 in R1. This means Please Perform: Checklist item: 41. This is CM/SM separation.
Use time scale to the CM/SM separation time stamp noted earlier. Press ROGER when you are 20 seconds away from the separation, or if the time of CM/SM sep has already passed.
Next we will trigger the CM/SM separation.
The SM is now separated and drifting away from the Command Module.
Transfer attitude control to the CM RCS.
This completes the CM/SM separation. Yaw back to 0 degrees yaw. Press ROGER when done.
Press PRO on the DSKY to proceed to V06 N61. This shows the predicted landing zone as Latitude and Longitude, and if the entry should start with heads up (+1) or heads down (-1).
Let us set up the Entry Monitoring System (EMS).
Set the EMS Function to RNG SET.
This value is found on the PAD as RTGO EMS. Use the thumb rocker to set this to 1200 nmi. Press ROGER when done.
Set the EMS function to V0 SET (initial entry velocity), the velocity at Entry Interface.

Use the thumb rocker to slew the scroll so that the display line aligns with the entry velocity of 25.500 ft/s. If you look at the PAD, the parameter VI0 shows where the line should be aligned. For lunar entry, this is much higher. For now, you can leave it on the line and if desired, tweak it slightly to match the PAD.
Set the EMS Function to ENTRY. This mode will allow the EMS to track our entry profile on the scroll.
Press PRO on the DSKY to advance to P63.
P63 initially displays V06 N64, showing the current drag acceleration, velocity and range to splash. Key V16E to allow the program to monitor these values so they update/refresh automatically.
The program will mainly keep you updated with the drag acceleration, and will automatically move to P64 at 0.05g. R1 shows this value, and when R1 shows 00005 (0.05), entry has started.
Using orbital view, focus on the CM and use timescale until the CM is close (but not yet passed) the EI mark. P64 will start once 0.05g is detected. Press ROGER when P64 has started.
Set the ENTRY 0.05G switch to UP. This will allow the EMS scroll to move when the EMS Mode is set to NORMAL later.
The the CMC mode to AUTO. This gives command of the space craft attitude to the CMC.
Allow the EMS RSI (Roll Stability Indicator to function) by setting ENTRY ROLL to UP.
Set the EMS mode to Normal to start the monitoring.

Guidance will guide the command module down but always be prepared to take over by switching to CMC FREE or SCS. For Earth Entry, guidance will try to constantly fly heads down/lift up for a safe entry (this is not the case for Lunar Entry).
The roll pointer on the EMS will now show you the correct up/down direction, and is used to maneuver through the atmosphere.
P64 will decide the next step based on many factors, such as vertical speed. For Earth Entry, it will move to P67.
When in P67, roll is used to guide the capsules lift vector to control the G-loads. The EMS will draw a line showing the G force and velocity.
If the roll index needle points up (your heads point down towards Earth), the lift vector points up and should reduce your G-load, or in this case, keep it as low as possible.
It is impossible to skip the atmosphere for Earth Entry. In Lunar Entry you can and will skip if you constantly keep the lift vector pointing up while velocities is above 25.500 ft/s.

If you want to try some manual maneuvering and see how if affects the entry profile, switch to SCS or CMC FREE, but make sure you do not point the lift vector down during this lesson (to keep things safe).
Monitor the G loads and velocity left on the EMS and the ACCEL G gauge, the attitude on the FDAI 1, and the Altimeter. When the Altimeter is <50.000 ft, press ROGER.
This transitions the flight from the SPS DEORBIT & ENTRY checklist to the EARTH LANDING checklist.
ARM the pyros for the chutes.
Enable the Earth Landing System (ELS) to allow deploying chutes.
The chute cover is automatically deployed but for redundancy, deploy it manually as well.
Drogues deployed. Press the manual trigger for this as well (redundancy).
Main chutes will deploy at ~10.000 ft altitude.
Main chutes are out!
For redundancy, manually trigger the main chute deployment as well.
These next steps are pre-splashdown steps and RCS dump/purge.
Wait for 3000 ft altitude.
This terminates the purge.
Wait for 800 ft altitude.
Wait for splashdown.

And splash! Good job, this completes the lesson. It sure contained a lot but you should now have a good overview of the main events. Going forward you should try Lesson 9B to continue learning the entry procedures with less hand holding.

Title: Lesson 9A - Atmospheric Entry
Description: Atmospheric Entry is a demanding phase of the mission. A lot of preparations are needed, and the last part of the spacecraft, the command module capsule, will make the final journey and splash down into the ocean. This lesson will use the SPS to set the trajectory back through the atmosphere, and the computer to guide the capsule through.
BriefingText:
BRIEFING

Atmospheric Entry is the last phase of any Apollo Mission and must be carefully planned and executed.
It's an involved mission phase and it's important to double check the steps and the values.

In this lesson we will go through the steps needed to perform the entry burn using the SPS, then separate from the Service Module.
Using what's commonly referred to as the 60's, namely Program 61 - 67 on the Command Module computer, we can prepare the computer for entry.

P61 - Entry Preparation
P62 - CM/SM Separation and Preentry Maneuver
P63 - Entry - Initialization
P64 - Entry - post 0.05g
P65 - Entry - Up control
P66 - Entry - Ballistic
P67 - Final Phase

We will start orienting the CSM to retrograde direction, before using P30 and P40 to perform the needed burn.
Then we will follow checklists and set up the computer for entry.

The EMS, Entry Monitoring System, is heavily used during entry and will display the optimal entry path.

After the 60's, the parachute deployment sequence starts, before splashing down into the ocean.


Good luck!
